Constructing a Sector Neutral Portfolio

One of the drawbacks of portfolio constructing based on factor selection is that you can concentrate your portfolio in certain sectors. And there are valid reasons to avoid such sectors (unfavorable macroeconomic environment, could be exposed to unwanted risks)

Deviation - Demonstration of group_by() function in R

The most important concept in this section is the usage of group_by() function from dplyr. The group_by() function in R is used to split a large data set by variables and then apply other functions to gain insights. For instance, consider the simple example below in which the group_by() function is used in conjunction with the summarize() function in which we input functions like mean(), n(), sum().

# Load necessary library
library(dplyr)

# Sample sales data
sales_data <- data.frame(
  region = c("North", "South", "North", "East", "South", "East"),
  sales = c(100, 150, 200, 120, 180, 110)
)

# Sum sales per region
total_sales_per_region <- sales_data %>%
  group_by(region) %>%
  summarize(total_sales = sum(sales))

The n() function counts the number of elements corresponding to the group it belongs to. Take a look at another example below.

# Filter regions with total sales greater than 250
high_sales_regions <- sales_data %>%
  group_by(region) %>%
  filter(sum(sales) > 250)

We can use other functions such as mutate(), filter(), and etc.

One thing to note is that the group_by() function alone doesnt really achieve anything; only when we use it with other functions do we see a change.

# Convert price file to xts object
KOR_price <- as.xts(KOR_price, order.by = as.Date(rownames(KOR_price)))

# Calculate returns
ret <- Return.calculate(KOR_price) %>% xts::last(252)

# Select 30 stocks based on highest 12-month returns
ret_12m <- ret %>% sapply(function(x) prod(1 + x) - 1)
invest_mom_12m <- rank(-ret_12m) <= 30

Notes

  • The reason for converting to an xts object is due to how Return.calculate() behaves when used with xts versus a data frame. When used on a data frame, any NA values will result in NA returns. With xts, Return.calculate() will ignore NA values.
  • Using braces {} around the functional expression in sapply() does not change the result.

A bit of subtlety to mention; in the aes() function, we specify label= parameter as geom_text() function looks for the label values to display on the chart. Thus, by specifying n as the label value, we make sure the counts are displayed next to the columns.

Neutralizing sector effects

Notice that the momentum factor is concentrated in the tech sector. Now, we could in theory decide whether we want our portfolio to be exposed to certain sectors or not. For instance, if we are aware momentum sorted portfolio will be concentrated in some sectors and that we have a positive bias regarding those sectors, we could purposely not neutralize by sector.

However, quants prefer to be agnostic by nature, I think; thus, we could choose to neutralize sector effects.

This is done by grouping all stocks by sectors and standardizing the returns within each sector. Then, even though the 12m return of a stock is high compared to the average of all stocks, if its return is relatively lower compared with its peers in the same sector, then it will receive a lower standardized score. Therefore, we will be in effect forcing a more strict standard for stocks that are included in a sector that performs well.

While the grouped scaling will return values for stocks that do not have SEC_NM_KOR values, including them in our analysis will be sloppy practice, since we are not scaling by a specific sector, but instead stocks identified as NA will be scaled within the NA group. Thus, to prevent ranking these stocks, we will manually input NA values for stocks that have NA sector names values.

Now we move on to implementation.scale() function will be used to standardize the returns (subtract mean and divide by sdv). Also, we will include both z-scores without sector grouping and z-score with sector grouping, to see the differences.

sector_neutral <- dt %>% 
  select(, , SEC_NM_KOR) %>% 
  mutate(ret = ret_12m, z_score = scale(ret)) %>% 
  group_by(SEC_NM_KOR) %>% 
  mutate(z_score_sector = scale(ret), 
         z_score_sector = ifelse(is.na(SEC_NM_KOR), NA, z_score_sector))

Now, we use the sector-neutralized z-score to rank momentum stocks and construct our new portfolio.

# Rank using sector-neutralized z-score
invest_mom_neutralized <- rank(-sector_neutral$z_score_sector) <= 30

# Use logical vector to subset data set
sector_neutral[invest_mom_neutralized,] %>%

We see that the new portfolio is less concentrated, though we still invest in nine names from the tech sector.

Imposing a max constraint on sector concentration

If for some reason, we have a very strong reason to not concentrate on a a specific sector, we could impose a maximum constraint (for instance, we would like to restrict ourself from investing more than 5 names per sector) and proceed to invest in the next best ranks.

For methodology, we could use the group_by() function to select the 5 lowest ranks per sector and output a subset of the original data set that has five best performing stocks (in terms of factor) for each sector. Then among these selected stocks, we select the 30 lowest ranked stocks.

The code sector_neutral %>% mutate(ranked = rank(-sector_neutral$z_score_sector)) does not work on its own because sector_neutral is a grouped data frame. Thus, mutate() automatically applies group-wise. Hence, we must ungroup the data set first.

# Ungroup df
sector_neutral_ungrouped <- ungroup(sector_neutral)

# Create new column
sector_neutral_constraint <- sector_neutral_ungrouped %>% mutate(ranked = rank(-sector_neutral$z_score_sector))

Notice rank() function will also rank the NA values but rank them last.

Next, we extract the five lowest ranked names within each sector using group_by() function and slice_min().

# Extract five best per sector
sector_neutral_constraint <- sector_neutral_constraint %>%
  group_by(SEC_NM_KOR) %>%
  slice_min(ranked, n = 5) %>%
  ungroup()

sector_neutral_constraint <- sector_neutral_constraint[rank(sector_neutral_constraint$ranked) <= 30,]
head(sector_neutral_constraint)
## # A tibble: 6  7
##             SEC_NM_KOR   ret z_score[,1] z_score_sector ranked

Notice with this cap, we have successfully capped out concentration at max five names per sector. Whether this methodology produces higher risk-adjusted returns in the long run compared to the unconstrained method is another subject.

Joel Greenblatts Magic Formula

Next, we look at a portfolio combining value and quality factors. The idea is as simple as it sounds. There are fundamentally sound reasons why looking into stocks with good quality and value score, as we may be able to screen out potential value traps (in contrast to sorting portfolios solely based on value factor) and over valued stocks (in contrast to sorting portfolios solely based on quality factor).

One of the main value + quality portfolio samples is oen constructed using the magic formula advocated by famous investor Joel Greenblatt.

Relationship between quality and value factor

First, we want to see what are the possible implications of using a combination of value and quality score to construct a portfolio.

Thus, we first look at basic relationships between those two factors.

# Import financial statements data sheet and valuation data
KOR_value <- read.csv("KOR_valuation_clean.csv")
KOR_fs <- readRDS("KOR_fs_clean.Rds")

KOR_value$X <- str_pad(KOR_value$X, 6,"left", 0)

Spearman vs Pearson

It might not be appropriate to find the pearson correlation between GPA, a quality factor, and PBR, a value factor, as both are on different scales. Instead, we could try to find the z-score of these two factors and then calculate the pearson correlation, or find the spearman correlation (pearson correlation between ranking values).

Raw correlation vs z-score correlation

When calculating GPA scores, we have to take into account that depending on the date we have collected data, the availability of most recent data differs.

Specifically, if we are in one of Jan, Feb, March, or April, we have to use data from two years ago.

## [1] 0.1672611

Obvious only when thinking about it mathematically, correlation is just the average of z-scores, so taking correlation of z-scores is essentially the same as taking correlation of the original pair.

Spearman correlation
# Plot ranked values
dt_rank <- data.frame(
  stock_code = dt$`stock code`, 
  PBR_rank = rank(dt$PBR), 
  GPA_rank = rank(-dt$GPA))

dt_rank %>% ggplot(aes(x = PBR_rank, y = GPA_rank)) +
  geom_point() +
  ggtitle("Scatterplot of ranked values for GPA vs PBR")

# Compute spearman correlation
cor(dt$PBR, -dt$GPA, method = 'spearman', use = 'complete.obs') %>% round(4)
## [1] -0.0951
cor(dt_rank$PBR_rank, dt_rank$GPA_rank, method = 'pearson', use = 'complete.obs') %>% round(4)
## [1] -0.0656
Visualization of PBR and GPA relationship using quantile summaries

Next, we will divide PBR to quantiles and find the average GPA corresponding to each PBR quantile. We use bar plots to visualize mean_gpa corresponding to each quantile to see whether there is a monotonic relationship between PBR and GPA.

dt %>%
  mutate(quantile_pbr = ntile(PBR, 5)) %>%
  filter(!is.na(quantile_pbr)) %>%
  group_by(quantile_pbr) %>%
  summarise(mean_gpa = mean(GPA, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = quantile_pbr, y = mean_gpa)) +
  geom_col() +
  xlab('PBR') + ylab('GPA')

We see that as stocks corresponding to lower PBR (belonging to 1st quantile) have lower mean GPA scores. That is, a value stock tends to have low quality score (measured using GPA).

Now we go back to actually constructing a portfolio based on the magic formula.

Constructing long-only portfolio based on magic formula

There are two important metrics to consider:

  1. Earnings yield (representing value of stock)
  2. Return on Capital (representing quality of stock)

Some important caveats of the magic formula:

  • Many investors use PER instead of earnings yield and ROE instead of ROC, due to insufficient data
  • Return on capital is a subjective measure whose precise calculation depending on the investor calculating the metric

However, we can construct the original magic formula portfolio using data we have collected.

Earnings Yield

First, when calculating earnings yield or return on capital, we need to decide on the return metric to use for the numerator. Usually, we use \[NOPAT = EBIT(1-t)\] where t is the marginal tax rate.

To calculate Earnings yield, the denominator is enterprise value, or EV.

\[EV = \text{market value of equity} + \text{market value of debt} - cash\]

is usually how we calculate EV, based on Aswath Damodaran.

In our case, we will define EV as market value of equity plus net debt, where net debt is defined as total debt - leftover cash. Leftover cash is residual cash after subtracting (-non-cash working capital); that is, if non-cash working capital is negative, we subtract this quantity from cash to get residual cash. This residual cash is indeed the leftover cash.

\[\text{residual cash} = - max(0, - + )\]

= ( ) / ( + - )

= ( ) / ( + - max(0, - +))

is how we calculate it.

library(stringr)
library(dplyr)
# Set num_col depending on date of data collection
if ( lubridate::month(Sys.Date()) %in% c(1,2,3,4) ) {
  num_col = str_which(colnames(KOR_fs[[1]]), as.character(lubridate::year(Sys.Date()) - 2 - years_elapsed_since_2023))
} else {
  num_col = str_which(colnames(KOR_fs[[1]]), as.character(lubridate::year(Sys.Date()) - 1 - years_elapsed_since_2023))
}

# subtract 1 from num_col to reflect that 1st column is character column. When we apply arithmetic operations later, we will have to disregard the 1st column
num_col <- num_col - 1
num_col
## [1] 2
# Calculate EBIT
magic_ebit <- (KOR_fs$""[-1] + KOR_fs$""[-1] + KOR_fs$""[-1])[num_col]

# Calculate EV
magic_MV_equity <- KOR_value$PER * KOR_fs$''[num_col+1]
magic_debt <- KOR_fs$""[num_col + 1]
magic_excess_cash1 <-  (KOR_fs$''[-1] - (KOR_fs$""[-1] - KOR_fs$""[-1]))[num_col]
magic_excess_cash1[magic_excess_cash1 < 0] <- 0
magic_excess_cash2 <- KOR_fs$[num_col + 1] - magic_excess_cash1

magic_EV <- magic_MV_equity + magic_debt - magic_excess_cash2

# Earnings Yield
magic_EY = magic_ebit / magic_EV

Note

  • There are 1111 NA values, where most of them are produced from the NA values regarding PER data. There are over 1000 data points with NA values regarding PER data. I believe the reason for this is because I used instead of when setting the numerator, when in fact the former financial account is missing for most stocks.

  • Realizing above point, we should collect data again regarding valuation ratios by using instead of .

Return on Capital (ROC)

Invested capital usually excludes non-interest bearing liabilities from total assets. Or we could add net debt (interest bearing liability - cash) to BV of equity. Whatever we do, the fundamental idea of invested capital is the book value of total operating assets.

The formula advocated by Aswath Damodaran is: \[IC = \text{BV of equity} + \text{BV of debt} - Cash\]

# Calculate ROC 
magic_ic = ((KOR_fs$''[-1] - KOR_fs$''[-1]) +
              (KOR_fs$''[-1] - KOR_fs$''[-1]))[num_col]
magic_roc = magic_ebit / magic_ic

Next, we rank portfolios by magic formula and construct our long-only portfolios. We simply rank the summation of the ranked values for each factor.

Also, higher roc and earnings yield imply higher risk premium, so we rank the negative values.

# Rank portfolio
invest_magic <- (rank(rank(-magic_roc) + rank(-magic_EY))) <= 30

# Check portfolio constituents

KOR_ticker[invest_magic,] %>% select('', '', '', '') %>% 
  mutate(earnings_yield = round(magic_EY[invest_magic,], 4),
         roc = round(magic_roc[invest_magic,], 4)
  )

Handling outliers and Combining Factors

Now, when we construct factor portfolios, it is inevitable to confront with outlier names. For instance, is it always good to include a stock that had 1000% return over the past 12 months? Or is it good that a companys ROE is 100%?

Definitely, we have to make discretionary decisions when confronting these issues. Hence, before we make these decisions, we first identify these outliers.

Trimming: Deleting Outliers

# Use percent_rank() to trim top and bottom 1% values
value_trim <- KOR_value %>% select(PBR) %>%
  mutate(PBR = ifelse(percent_rank(PBR) < 0.01, NA, PBR),
         PBR = ifelse(percent_rank(PBR) >0.99, NA, PBR)
         )

value_trim %>% ggplot(aes(x = PBR)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.3)

Winsorizing: Replace outliers

Another common way is to set a threshold on each tailside (e.g., 1% and 99%) and replace values that exceed these thresholds with the threshold values (i.e., 1% and 99% percentile values).

# Winsorize using 1% and 99% threshold values
value_winsorize <- KOR_value %>% select(PBR) %>%
  mutate(PBR = ifelse(percent_rank(PBR) < 0.01, quantile(., 0.01, na.rm = TRUE), PBR),
         PBR = ifelse(percent_rank(PBR) > 0.99, quantile(., 0.99, na.rm = TRUE), PBR)
         )

value_winsorize %>% ggplot(aes(x = PBR)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.3)

Compared with the trimming method, we see that there is an increase in extreme values (long histogram).

Combining multiple factors

When constructing factor portfolios, adding ranks have its own pros as they nullify extreme values.

However, adding ranks can be troublesome when you want to seriously manage money.

That usually occurs when you have distorted NA values for each data set. This is confirmed in the next visual.

We see that min_rank() method does not parse NA values; that is, it doesnt rank NA values, unlike rank().

We use min_rank() in order to visualize the caveats of adding ranks of data vectors with varying NA values.

KOR_value %>%
  mutate_all(list(~min_rank(.))) %>%
  pivot_longer(c(PER, PBR, PSR, PCR), names_to = "metric", values_to = "value") %>% head()

Next, we apply pivot_longer to convert from wide to long format, organizing into a two-column data frame with key-value pairs.

KOR_value %>%
  mutate_all(list(~min_rank(.))) %>%
  pivot_longer(c(PER, PBR, PSR, PCR), names_to = "metric", values_to = "value") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = value)) +
  geom_histogram() +
  facet_wrap(~metric)

As we can see above, PBR and PSR values do not suffer from too many missing data, while PCR and PER have many less data points from missing observation.

Notes

  • We used mutate_all() here since we want to apply a function to all the columns of data frame.
  • list() inside of the mutate_all() is there if we want to apply a list of functions to the columns.
  • ~ notation is a foreshadow that instructs R that the superceding code will be an anonymous function.
  • gather() is used to transform wide to long format, which is more adapt for using ggplot.
  • face_wrap() is used to create multiple panels within the graph, separated by key values.

Now, to remedy above phenomenon, we find the z-score of these ranks. This will unify the x-scale once again while at the same time maintaining the ordered property of the current features.

KOR_value %>%
  mutate_all(list(~min_rank(.))) %>%
  mutate_all(list(~scale(.))) %>%
  pivot_longer(c(PER, PBR, PSR, PCR), names_to = "metric", values_to = "value") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = value)) +
  geom_histogram() +
  facet_wrap(. ~metric)

We see that the x-axis is unified. Now we can add these z-scores to find multi-factor portfolios.

Multi Factor Portfolio Construction

Finally, we use following measurements to construct multifactors.

  • Quality: ROE, Gross Margin, Operating Cash Flow
  • Value: PBR, PER, PSR, PCR
  • Momentum: 3 month return, 6 month return, 12 month return

For this section, we will use following data sheets.

  • KOR_fs: financial statements for all publicly listed companies
  • KOR_value: PBR, PCR, PSR, and PER values
  • KOR_price: price series for all publicly listed companies
  • KOR_ticker: ticker data

Reflections

For this section, there were some important details that we had to consider.

  1. When calculating market cap for magic formula, we used PER data from the KOR_value csv sheet. However, there were over 1000 NA values regarding PER data, probably because we used instead of , and the former account was not used anymore.

  2. Should look into constructing long-short portfolios instead of just long-only portfolios.

  3. Ranking is a powerful way to standardize factors. However, we must be careful to not aggregate ranks with widely differing ranges. In such case, we should standardize ranks before adding them up. Rank > Scale > Cross-sectional Aggregation > Rank > Cross-sectional Aggregation is the general flow for constructing multi-factor portfolio.

  4. Verify the selected names are consistent with out methodology.
